1":"1501","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1420":"1420","1431":"1431","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","Blois, Loir-et-Cher, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"Blois, Loir-et-Cher, Centre, Frankrijk","Chartres-de-Bretagne, Ille-et-Vilaine, Bretagne, France":"Chartres-de-Bretagne, Ille-et-Vilaine, Bretagne, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1400–1450":"1400–1450","1400–1455":"1400–1455","1420–1450":"1420–1450","1425–1501":"1425–1501","1431–1476":"1431–1476","1440–Male":"1440–Deceased","1450–Female":"1450–Deceased","1369–Male":"1369–Deceased","1425":"1425","1369":"1369","1501":"1501","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1420":"1420","1431":"1431","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","Blois, Loir-et-Cher, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"Blois, Loir-et-Cher, Centre, France","Chartres-de-Bretagne, Ille-et-Vilaine, Bretagne, France":"Chartres-de-Bretagne, Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"GAILLARD","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Philippe, Pierre, Andre, Andree, Ketly, Marcel, Mirlande, Monique.","French: nickname from <i>gaillard</i> ‘vigorous, strong’ (ultimately from Celtic <i>galia</i> ‘strength’). This surname (in any of the two possible senses; see also below) is also found in Haiti.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gailhard</i>, composed of the elements <i>gail</i> ‘powerful, lusty, cheerful’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’."],"variants":[{"name":"Gailliard","meanings":["French: variant of   Gaillard   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Gaylord","meanings":["English (southern, of Norman origin): variant of <b>Gaylard</b> altered by folk etymology, from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Gaillart</i>, <i>Gallard</i>, <i>Galliard</i>, representing either the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gailhard</i> (composed of elements meaning ‘powerful, lusty, cheerful’ + ‘hard, firm, resilient, strong’) or Old French <i>gaillard</i>, <i>gaillart</i> ‘vigorous, powerful, strong’. Alternatively, from Middle English <i>gaillard</i>, <i>galiard</i> ‘brave, strong, valiant’, also ‘lively, gay, gaily dressed’.","Altered form of <b>Gaylard</b>, itself an Anglicized form of French   Gaillard  , which was brought to England by the Huguenots.","In some cases also an Americanized form of French   Gaillard  ."]}]},{"name":"Mathurin","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Modern name meaning ‘bear’, a simplified form of the earlier <i>Mathghamhain</i>, borne by a brother of Brian Boru, High King of Ireland in the early 11th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mahon","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Mathúin ."]}]},{"name":"Michel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical.  See  <b>Michael</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Michael","meanings":["form of a common biblical name (meaning ‘who is like God?’ in Hebrew) borne by one of the archangels, the protector of the ancient Hebrews, who is also regarded as a saint of the Catholic Church. In the Middle Ages, Michael was regarded as captain of the heavenly host (see Revelation 12:7–9), symbol of the Church Militant, and patron of soldiers. He was often depicted bearing a flaming sword. The name is also borne by a Persian prince and ally of Belshazzar mentioned in the Book of Daniel. Since the early 1900s it has been one of the most enduringly popular boys' names in the English-speaking world.  See also  Michal ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mathurin Michel GAILLARD I was born in 1400, in Chartres-de-Bretagne, Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany, France as the son of Robert Gaillard. He had at least 4 sons and 1 daughter with Catherine Denizement. He died in 1450, in Blois, Loir-et-Cher, Centre, France, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1400–1450":"1400–1450","1400–1455":"140